Here's how to implement all three:

**1 & 2. Guard navigation in `AppShell.xaml.cs`** — use `GetDeferral()` for the async dialog:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**3. Custom "Cancel" back button** — add `BackButtonBehavior` in `EditProductPage.xaml`:

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage"
             Title="Edit Product">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

In your ViewModel (or code-behind):

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    // This triggers OnNavigating, so the guard above will fire
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it you'd have a race condition.
- `args.Cancel()` prevents the navigation when the user taps "Stay."
- `BackButtonBehavior.TextOverride` replaces the default back arrow with "Cancel" text.
- The `Command` on `BackButtonBehavior` replaces the default back behavior, so it calls your `GoToAsync("..")` which flows through the same `OnNavigating` guard.
- Expose a `HasUnsavedChanges` property on your page (or check via BindingContext) so the guard knows when to prompt.
